etween the developing research practices of ethnology, works offiction, autobiography, travel narratives, Native oratory, and sign languagesgave imaginative shape to imperial activity in the western borderlands. In literary andperformative settings that range from the U.S./Mexico borderlands to the GreatLakes region of Tecumseh's Pan-Indian Confederacy and the hallowed halls oflearned societies in New York and Philadelphia, Ethnology and Empire modelsan interdisciplinary approach to networks of peoples, spaces, and communicationpractices that transformed the boundaries of U.S. empire through atransnational and scientific archive. Emphasizing the culturally transformativeimpacts western expansionism and Indian Removal, Ethnology and Empire reimaginesU.S. literary and cultural production for future conceptions of hemisphericAmerican literatures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAnthropological linguisticszNorth AmericaxHistoryy19th century. 0aBorderlandszNorth AmericaxHistoryy19th century. 0aEthnologyzNorth AmericaxHistoryy19th century. 0aIndians of North AmericaxLanguages. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Native American.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479872411.001.0001zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479872411zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479872411/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA